From the context provided, we can see the following relevant excerpt from clause 6.2:
"The organization shall establish anti-bribery management system objectives at relevant functions and levels. The anti-bribery management system objectives shall:
a) be consistent with the anti-bribery policy;
b) be measurable (if practicable);
c)"

However, the context provided only includes two elements (a and b). To fully answer the question, we should also consider the elements listed under "determine" in another part of the context:
"determine:
— what will be done;
— what resources will be required;
— who will be responsible;
— when the objectives will be achieved;
— how the results will be evaluated and reported;
— who will impose sanctions or penalties."

While these are separate actions rather than elements of the anti-bribery objectives themselves, they are part of the planning process to achieve the objectives. The actual elements of the anti-bribery management system objectives are listed in the context as:
1. Consistent with the anti-bribery policy
2. Measurable (if practicable)

Thus, there are two elements specifically listed for establishing anti-bribery management system objectives in clause 6.2.

Clause 6.2 mentions that the organization shall establish anti-bribery management system objectives at relevant functions and levels. It further specifies that these objectives must:
- be consistent with the anti-bribery policy;
- be measurable (if practicable);
- take into account applicable factors referred to in 4.1, the requirements referred to in 4.2, and the bribery risks identified in 4.5;
- be achievable;
- be monitored;
- be communicated in accordance with 7.4;
- be updated as appropriate.

Additionally, the organization shall determine:
- what will be done;
- what resources will be required;
- who will be responsible;
- when the objectives will be achieved;
- how the results will be evaluated and reported;
- who will impose sanctions or penalties.

From this, we can see that there are multiple items that need to be determined when planning how to achieve anti-bribery objectives. These include the actions to be taken, resources required, responsibilities, timelines, evaluation methods, and sanctions.
